{"title_page": "Thrombophlebitis", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Thrombophlebitis\n| synonyms        = Phlebitis<ref name=med/>\n| image           = Great_saphenous_vein_thrombosis_05091312009.jpg\n| caption         = Ultrasonographic image showing thrombosis of the [[great saphenous vein]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = Skin redness<ref name=med/>\n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = Smoking, Lupus<ref name=med/>\n| diagnosis       = Doppler ultrasound, Venography<ref name=med/>\n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = Blood thinners, Pain medication<ref name=med/>\n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Thrombophlebitis''' is a [[phlebitis]] (''[[inflammation]]'' of a [[vein]]) related to a [[thrombus]] (blood clot).<ref name=\"pmid16868304\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Torpy JM, Burke AE, Glass RM |title=JAMA patient page. Thrombophlebitis |journal=[[Journal of the American Medical Association|JAMA]] |volume=296 |issue=4 |pages=468 |date=July 2006 |pmid=16868304 |doi=10.1001/jama.296.4.468 }}</ref> When it occurs repeatedly in different locations, it is known as '''thrombophlebitis migrans''' (migratory thrombophlebitis).<ref name=\"Jinna\">{{cite web |last1=Jinna |first1=Sruthi |last2=Khoury |first2=John |title=Migratory Thrombophlebitis |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547702/ |website=StatPearls |publisher=StatPearls Publishing |date=2020}}</ref>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nThe following symptoms or signs are often associated with thrombophlebitis, although thrombophlebitis is not restricted to the veins of the [[lower limbs|legs]].<ref name=\"med\">{{cite web|title=Thrombophlebitis: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|url=https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/001108.htm|website=medlineplus.gov|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"emed\">{{cite web|title=Thrombophlebitis Clinical Presentation: History, Physical Examination, Causes|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1086399-clinical#showall|website=emedicine.medscape.com|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Pain]] (area affected)\n* Skin redness/[[inflammation]] \n* [[Edema]] ([[ankle]] and [[foot]])\n* [[Vein]]s being hard and cord-like\n* Tenderness (leg)\n}}\n===Complications===\nIn terms of complications, one of the most serious occurs when the superficial blood clot is associated with a [[deep vein thrombosis]]; this can then dislodge, traveling through the [[heart]] and occluding the dense [[capillary]] network of the [[lungs]] This is a [[pulmonary embolism]] which can be life-threatening.<ref name=sci/>\n\n==Causes==\n[[File:Deep vein thrombosis of the right leg.jpg|thumb|130 px|Deep vein thrombosis/ right leg]]\nThrombophlebitis causes include disorders related to increased tendency for [[blood clotting]] and reduced speed of blood in the veins such as prolonged immobility; prolonged traveling (sitting) may promote a blood clot leading to thrombophlebitis but this occurs relatively less. High estrogen states such as pregnancy, [[estrogen replacement therapy]], or oral contraceptives are associated with an increased risk of thrombophlebitis.<ref name=med/><ref name=emed/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Philbrick|first1=John T.|last2=Shumate|first2=Rebecca|last3=Siadaty|first3=Mir S.|last4=Becker|first4=Daniel M.|title=Air Travel and Venous Thromboembolism: A Systematic Review|journal=Journal of General Internal Medicine|date=23 October 2016|volume=22|issue=1|pages=107\u2013114|doi=10.1007/s11606-006-0016-0|pmc=1824715|issn=0884-8734|pmid=17351849}}</ref> \n\nSpecific disorders associated with thrombophlebitis include superficial thrombophlebitis which affects veins near the skin surface, [[deep vein thrombosis]] which affects deeper veins, and [[pulmonary embolism]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Superficial Thrombophlebitis: Background, Pathophysiology, Etiology|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/463256-overview#showall|website=eMedicine|publisher=Medscape|accessdate=23 October 2016|date=12 July 2016}}</ref> \n\nThose with familial [[Coagulopathy|clotting disorders]] such as [[protein S deficiency]], [[protein C deficiency]], or [[factor V Leiden]] are also at increased risk of thrombophlebitis. Thrombophlebitis can be found in people with [[vasculitis]] including [[Beh\u00e7et's disease]]. Thrombophlebitis migrans can be a sign of malignancy \u2013 [[Trousseau sign of malignancy]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Varki|first1=Ajit|title=Trousseau's syndrome: multiple definitions and multiple mechanisms|journal=Blood|date=15 September 2007|volume=110|issue=6|pages=1723\u20131729|doi=10.1182/blood-2006-10-053736|language=en|issn=0006-4971|pmid=17496204|pmc=1976377}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nThe diagnosis for thrombophlebitis is primarily based on the appearance of the affected area. Frequent checks of the [[pulse]], [[blood pressure]], and [[temperature]] may be required. If the cause is not readily identifiable, tests may be performed to determine the cause, including the following:<ref name=med/><ref name=emed/>\n* [[Doppler ultrasound]]\n* Extremity [[arteriography]]\n* [[Blood coagulation]] studies ([[Blood clotting tests]])\n\n==Prevention==\nPrevention consists of walking, drinking fluids and if currently hospitalized, changing of [[Intravenous|IV lines]].<ref name=med/> Walking is especially suggested after a long period seated, particularly when one travels.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tamparo|first1=Carol D.|title=Diseases of the Human Body|date=2016|publisher=F.A. Davis|isbn=9780803657915|page=292|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eMOCCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA292&dq=prevention+thrombophlebitis#v=onepage&q=prevention%20thrombophlebitis&f=false|accessdate=23 October 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Treatment==\n[[File:Ibuprofen3DanJ.gif|thumb|Ibuprofen (NSAID)]]\nIn terms of treatment for this condition the individual may be advised to do the following: ''raise'' the affected area to decrease [[swelling (medical)|swelling]], and relieve  pressure off of the affected area so it will encounter less pain. In certain circumstances drainage of the clot might be an option. In general, treatment may include the following:<ref name=med/><ref name=emed/><ref name=\"sci\">{{cite book|last1=Raval|first1=P.|title=Thrombophlebitis\u2606|journal=Reference Module in Biomedical Sciences|date=1 January 2014|doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-801238-3.05368-X|url= |isbn=9780128012383}} </ref>\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Low molecular weight [[heparin]] \n* [[Warfarin]]\n* [[Surgery]]\n* Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory medications ([[NSAIDS]]) ([[Ibuprofen]])\n* Support [[stockings]] \n}}\n\n==Epidemiology==\nThrombophlebitis occurs almost equally between women and men, though males do have a slightly higher possibility. The average age of developing thrombophlebitis, based on analyzed incidents, is 54 for men and 58 for women.<ref name=sci/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mondor's disease]]\n*[[Phlebothrombosis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Sadick|first1=Neil S.|last2=Khilnani|first2=Neil|last3=Morrison|first3=Nick|title=Practical Approach to the Management and Treatment of Venous Disorders|date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9781447128915|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wO37msc718YC&pg=PA155&dq=Thrombophlebitis+treatment#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=23 October 2016|language=en}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Mulholland|first1=Michael W.|last2=Lillemoe|first2=Keith D.|last3=Doherty|first3=Gerard M.|last4=Maier|first4=Ronald V.|last5=Simeone|first5=Diane M.|last6=Upchurch|first6=Gilbert R.|title=Greenfield's Surgery: Scientific Principles & Practice|date=2012|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=9781451152920|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KkJc0XYVc0IC&pg=PT3947&dq=Thrombophlebitis+treatment#v=onepage&q=Thrombophlebitis%20treatment&f=false|accessdate=23 October 2016|language=en}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|I|80||i|80}}, {{ICD10|I|82|1|i|80}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|451}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = 001108\n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D013924\n| SNOMED CT       = 64156001\n}}\n{{Scholia|topic}}\n{{Vascular diseases}}\n{{Medicine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Vascular diseases]]\n[[Category:Inflammations]]\n[[Category:Diseases of veins, lymphatic vessels and lymph nodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Thrombophlebitis\n| synonyms        = Phlebitis<ref name=med/>\n| image           = Great_saphenous_vein_thrombosis_05091312009.jpg\n| caption         = Ultrasonographic image showing thrombosis of the [[great saphenous vein]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| symptoms        = Skin redness<ref name=med/>\n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = Smoking, Lupus<ref name=med/>\n| diagnosis       = Doppler ultrasound, Venography<ref name=med/>\n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = Blood thinners, Pain medication<ref name=med/>\n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Thrombophlebitis''' is a [[phlebitis]] (''[[inflammation]]'' of a [[vein]]) related to a [[thrombus]] (blood clot).<ref name=\"pmid16868304\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Torpy JM, Burke AE, Glass RM |title=JAMA patient page. Thrombophlebitis |journal=[[Journal of the American Medical Association|JAMA]] |volume=296 |issue=4 |pages=468 |date=July 2006 |pmid=16868304 |doi=10.1001/jama.296.4.468 }}</ref> When it occurs repeatedly in different locations, it is known as '''thrombophlebitis migrans''' (migratory thromb